		 	<span id="comment_score_64771548" class="score"> (<a href="#" onclick="getModalPrefs('modcommentlog', 'Moderation Comment Log', 64771548); return false"><span class=opt>Score:</span>4</a>, Insightful)</span></h4>
		</div>
		<div class="details">
			<span class="by"><span class="byby">by </span><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~The+Cat">The Cat</a>  <span class="uid"><a rel="nofollow" href="//slashdot.org/~The+Cat">( 19816 )</a></span></a></span><span class="writes" style="display:none"> writes:</span> 
			<span class="otherdetails" id="comment_otherdetails_64771548">		
		on Sunday September 08, 2024 @02:42AM (<span class="ind"></span><a rel="nofollow" href="//developers.slashdot.org/comments.pl?sid=23447868&amp;cid=64771548">#64771548</a>)
		<small> </small>
</span>
		</div>
	</div>
	<div class="commentBody">
		<div id="comment_body_64771548"><p>C and C++ are not "memory unsafe."</p><p><b>Your code</b> is memory unsafe.  Not the language.</p><p>C is a portable assembler. It is no more or less "unsafe" than machine language. It is neither defective nor is it inadequate. It is simply a tool. It is up to the developer to make it safe.</p></div>
	</div>

	<div class="commentSub" id="comment_sub_64771548">
